Summaries for TYMP Gene

Entrez Gene Summary for TYMP Gene

  • This gene encodes an angiogenic factor which promotes angiogenesis in vivo and stimulates the in vitro growth of a variety of endothelial cells. It has a highly restricted target cell specificity acting only on endothelial cells. Mutations in this gene have been associated with mitochondrial neurogastrointestinal encephalomyopathy. Multiple alternatively spliced transcript variants have been identified. [provided by RefSeq, Apr 2012]

GeneCards Summary for TYMP Gene

TYMP (Thymidine Phosphorylase) is a Protein Coding gene. Diseases associated with TYMP include mitochondrial dna depletion syndrome 1 and mitochondrial neurogastrointestinal encephalopathy disease. Among its related pathways are Bladder cancer and Porphyrin and chlorophyll metabolism. GO annotations related to this gene include growth factor activity and platelet-derived growth factor receptor binding.

UniProtKB/Swiss-Prot for TYMP Gene

  • TYPH_HUMAN,P19971

  • May have a role in maintaining the integrity of the blood vessels. Has growth promoting activity on endothelial cells, angiogenic activity in vivo and chemotactic activity on endothelial cells in vitro.

  • Catalyzes the reversible phosphorolysis of thymidine. The produced molecules are then utilized as carbon and energy sources or in the rescue of pyrimidine bases for nucleotide synthesis.

Molecular function for TYMP Gene

UniProtKB/Swiss-Prot CatalyticActivity:
Thymidine + phosphate = thymine + 2-deoxy-alpha-D-ribose 1-phosphate.
  • TYPH_HUMAN,P19971
UniProtKB/Swiss-Prot Function:
May have a role in maintaining the integrity of the blood vessels. Has growth promoting activity on endothelial cells, angiogenic activity in vivo and chemotactic activity on endothelial cells in vitro.
  • TYPH_HUMAN,P19971
UniProtKB/Swiss-Prot Function:
Catalyzes the reversible phosphorolysis of thymidine. The produced molecules are then utilized as carbon and energy sources or in the rescue of pyrimidine bases for nucleotide synthesis.
  • TYPH_HUMAN,P19971

UniProtKB/Swiss-Prot

TYPH_HUMAN
  • Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 1, MNGIE type (MTDPS1) [MIM:603041]: A multisystem disease associated with mitochondrial dysfunction. It is clinically characterized by onset between the second and fifth decades of life, ptosis, progressive external ophthalmoplegia, gastrointestinal dysmotility (often pseudoobstruction), diffuse leukoencephalopathy, cachexia, peripheral neuropathy, and myopathy. {ECO:0000269 PubMed:12177387, ECO:0000269 PubMed:9924029}. Note=The disease is caused by mutations affecting the gene represented in this entry.
